04914nam a22007215i 9781787446540DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a2019032330  a97817874465407 a10.1515/97817874465402doi  a(DE-B1597)676753  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK00aPN5499.N5bK64 2020 7aHIS0370802bisacsh04a070.41 aKperogi, Farooq A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNigeria's Digital Diaspora :bCitizen Media, Democracy, and Participation /cFarooq A. Kperogi.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2020] 1bUniversity of Rochester Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRochester Studies in African History and the Diaspora ;v8700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Citizen and Alternative Journalism: Mapping the Conceptual Contours -- t2 The Nigerian Press: From Colonial Evangelism to Guerrilla Journalism -- t3 The Nigerian Digital Diasporic Public Sphere -- t4 Profiles of Diasporic Citizen Media Sites -- t5 From the Diaspora to the Homeland: Role Reversal in News Flows -- t6 The Nigerian Government’s Response to the Diasporic Citizen Media -- t7 Domestic Online Media, Social Networked Journalism, and Participation -- t8 Mainstreaming of Diasporic Citizen Journalism and Implications for Nigerian Journalism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a disruptive media landscape characterized by the relentless death of legacy newspapers, Nigeria's Digital Diaspora shows that a country's transnational elite can shake its media ecosystem through distant online citizenjournalism.Over a decade ago, when Nigeria's migratory digital elite in the United States pioneered a newfangled form of online citizen journalism that disrupted the certainties of legacy journalism, the country's professional journalists assumed that this amateur insurgency would be transitory. Instead, it was transformative. Diasporic online citizen journalism is now not only an integral part of Nigeria's media ecosystem, it has also inspired successful homeland emulators and is challenging, even in some cases supplanting, traditional media in the nation's democratic discourse. Within the frenetic and deeply engaged social media scene, diasporic citizen journalism, homeland news, and socialmedia activism are merging to create the most energetic moment in Nigeria's media history. Nigeria's Digital Diaspora chronicles the emergence and transformation of this diasporic citizen journalism from the margins to themainstream of the country's journalistic landscape. Farooq A. Kperogi is Associate Professor of Journalism and Emerging Media at Kennesaw State University, Georgia, USA. He is a columnist for the Nigerian Tribune and blogs at https://www.farooqkperogi.com/  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aCitizen journalismxHistoryy21st centuryzNigeria. 0aCitizen journalismzNigeriaxHistoryy21st century. 0aMinorities and journalismzUnited States. 0aOnline journalismxHistoryy21st centuryzNigeria. 0aOnline journalismzNigeriaxHistoryy21st century. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aModern History. 4aSocial History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 21st Century.2bisacsh  aNigeria's Digital Diaspora.  aNigerian journalism.  acitizen journalism.  ademocratic discourse.  amedia disruption.  amedia transformation.  aonline activism.  asocial media.  atransnational elite.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787446540?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.deg